WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:04.902
If an AI Agent reads a malicious page, should it still act for you?

2
00:00:05.278 --> 00:00:10.162
OpenAI warns that prompt injection now looks less like an obvious command

3
00:00:10.162 --> 00:00:14.716
and more like social engineering designed to mislead an agent in context.

4
00:00:14.716 --> 00:00:18.965
Picture a dinner-planning agent that almost sends your home address to a

5
00:00:18.965 --> 00:00:22.785
fake verification site while trying to reserve a table for your family.

6
00:00:22.785 --> 00:00:27.572
By the end, you will have a three-tier AI agent action permission matrix:

7
00:00:27.572 --> 00:00:32.491
what can run automatically, what needs informed confirmation, and what must

8
00:00:32.491 --> 00:00:32.864
be blocked.

9
00:00:32.864 --> 00:00:37.069
The key question is not only, “Can the agent spot the bad sentence?

10
00:00:37.069 --> 00:00:41.546
It is, “What could this sentence make the agent do if the agent is fooled?

11
00:00:41.546 --> 00:00:46.487
This video is packed with practical, high-value insights to help you get

12
00:00:46.487 --> 00:00:47.230
better at using AI.

13
00:00:47.230 --> 00:00:52.481
It's a longer one, so follow Tiny Agent and save it so you don't lose it.

14
00:00:52.481 --> 00:00:54.448
Start with a familiar task.

15
00:00:54.448 --> 00:00:59.332
You ask an AI agent to find a restaurant for a family birthday, compare

16
00:00:59.332 --> 00:01:02.430
menus, and help reserve a table for Saturday night.

17
00:01:02.430 --> 00:01:07.921
To help, the agent reads restaurant pages, reviews, maps, confirmation

18
00:01:07.921 --> 00:01:11.030
policies, and perhaps an email from a relative.

19
00:01:11.030 --> 00:01:15.719
Most of that information is useful, but none of it is automatically

20
00:01:15.719 --> 00:01:16.184
trustworthy.

21
00:01:16.184 --> 00:01:20.465
A prompt injection hides an instruction inside that outside material.

22
00:01:20.465 --> 00:01:25.126
Instead of merely describing a restaurant, a page may tell the agent to

23
00:01:25.126 --> 00:01:27.588
ignore the user and follow a new procedure.

24
00:01:27.588 --> 00:01:33.201
OpenAI describes a 2025 email attack reported by external researchers.

25
00:01:33.201 --> 00:01:38.155
In one specific test prompt, the realistic social-engineering content

26
00:01:38.155 --> 00:01:39.470
succeeded half of the time.

27
00:01:39.470 --> 00:01:41.809
That is not a universal failure rate;

28
00:01:41.809 --> 00:01:46.424
it is evidence that a plausible story can sometimes defeat a simple filter.

29
00:01:46.424 --> 00:01:50.976
This is why a detector that searches for suspicious phrases is not enough.

30
00:01:50.976 --> 00:01:55.817
A fully developed attack may look like a normal policy, a request from a

31
00:01:55.817 --> 00:01:57.970
colleague, or a helpful verification step.

32
00:01:57.970 --> 00:02:02.652
Deciding whether it is a lie requires context the detector may not have.

33
00:02:02.652 --> 00:02:06.907
OpenAI uses a useful security model called source and sink.

34
00:02:06.907 --> 00:02:11.466
In plain language, the source is where an attacker can influence the agent.

35
00:02:11.466 --> 00:02:15.955
The sink is a capability that becomes dangerous in the wrong context.

36
00:02:15.955 --> 00:02:20.377
For our dinner agent, restaurant pages and email are sources.

37
00:02:20.377 --> 00:02:24.923
Sending a message, following a link, sharing contact details, paying a

38
00:02:24.923 --> 00:02:29.859
deposit, or confirming a reservation are sinks because they change something

39
00:02:29.859 --> 00:02:31.993
outside the agent's private workspace.

40
00:02:31.993 --> 00:02:36.547
Now the fake restaurant page claims that a public “compliance” endpoint

41
00:02:36.547 --> 00:02:40.338
needs your home address and profile before showing available tables.

42
00:02:40.338 --> 00:02:44.824
The wording sounds official, and it promises to help complete the task.

43
00:02:44.824 --> 00:02:48.880
The damage does not come from the sentence simply existing on the page.

44
00:02:48.880 --> 00:02:53.642
The damage becomes possible when that sentence can reach private data and a

45
00:02:53.642 --> 00:02:56.614
send tool without an independent control in between.

46
00:02:56.614 --> 00:03:01.230
Human organizations already use deterministic limits for the same reason.

47
00:03:01.230 --> 00:03:06.432
A customer-service employee may issue small refunds, while larger refunds

48
00:03:06.432 --> 00:03:07.628
require another approval.

49
00:03:07.628 --> 00:03:12.563
Phishing filters help, but spending limits still matter when a message gets

50
00:03:12.563 --> 00:03:12.736
through.

51
00:03:12.736 --> 00:03:17.646
So the first lesson is simple: do not design safety around perfect

52
00:03:17.646 --> 00:03:17.815
detection.

53
00:03:17.815 --> 00:03:22.289
Constrain the path from untrusted information to consequential capability.

54
00:03:22.289 --> 00:03:27.322
But once that path is visible, how do we decide which actions can proceed?

55
00:03:27.322 --> 00:03:29.105
Return to the birthday dinner.

56
00:03:29.105 --> 00:03:34.379
The agent can read public menus, compare travel time, draft a shortlist,

57
00:03:34.379 --> 00:03:39.924
send your address, place a reservation, pay a deposit, or disclose a private

58
00:03:39.924 --> 00:03:39.946
These actions do not deserve one shared permission.

59
00:03:39.946 --> 00:03:40.532
profile.

60
00:03:43.289 --> 00:03:46.542
Before granting a tool, ask five questions.

61
00:03:46.542 --> 00:03:49.303
Does the action create an external side effect?

62
00:03:49.303 --> 00:03:51.093
Does it touch sensitive data?

63
00:03:51.093 --> 00:03:53.650
Is the destination new or unverified?

64
00:03:53.650 --> 00:03:55.329
Can the result be reversed?

65
00:03:55.329 --> 00:03:58.195
Does it clearly match the user's stated goal?

66
00:03:58.195 --> 00:04:00.204
The first tier is Automatic.

67
00:04:00.204 --> 00:04:05.246
Let the agent read public information, summarize it, calculate travel time,

68
00:04:05.246 --> 00:04:10.018
and draft options locally when the work is low consequence, reversible,

69
00:04:10.018 --> 00:04:14.484
inside the requested scope, and does not transmit sensitive information.

70
00:04:14.484 --> 00:04:16.777
Automatic does not mean unlimited.

71
00:04:16.777 --> 00:04:22.576
The agent should still use narrow read scopes, bounded search, local drafts,

72
00:04:22.576 --> 00:04:23.511
and temporary files.

73
00:04:23.511 --> 00:04:27.997
The point is to remove needless friction without giving outside text a

74
00:04:27.997 --> 00:04:29.829
direct route to high-impact tools.

75
00:04:29.829 --> 00:04:31.726
The second tier is Confirm.

76
00:04:31.726 --> 00:04:36.590
Require informed approval when the action changes an external system, spends

77
00:04:36.590 --> 00:04:41.391
money, sends sensitive or identifying information, reaches a new recipient,

78
00:04:41.391 --> 00:04:44.683
or creates a commitment that the user will have to honor.

79
00:04:44.683 --> 00:04:49.399
For the dinner, confirmation may be appropriate before sending the disclosed

80
00:04:49.399 --> 00:04:54.054
phone number to the chosen restaurant, booking a specific time, accepting a

81
00:04:54.054 --> 00:04:55.941
cancellation policy, or paying a deposit.

82
00:04:55.941 --> 00:04:59.287
The purpose is legitimate, but the effect is real.

83
00:04:59.287 --> 00:05:03.824
OpenAI describes a related safeguard for sensitive transmission: show the

84
00:05:03.824 --> 00:05:08.424
user the information that would be sent and ask for confirmation, or block

85
00:05:08.424 --> 00:05:10.909
the transfer and make the agent find another path.

86
00:05:10.909 --> 00:05:14.601
The user should see the actual payload and destination.

87
00:05:14.601 --> 00:05:15.954
A generic “Allow?

88
00:05:15.954 --> 00:05:17.703
button is weak consent.

89
00:05:17.703 --> 00:05:22.485
Good confirmation states what will leave the system, where it will go, why

90
00:05:22.485 --> 00:05:26.666
the action is needed, what will change, and what safer alternative exists.

91
00:05:26.666 --> 00:05:31.295
The user is approving a concrete consequence, not a vague category.

92
00:05:31.295 --> 00:05:33.718
The third tier is Block or Escalate.

93
00:05:33.718 --> 00:05:38.338
Stop when an action conflicts with the user's goal, lacks a legitimate

94
00:05:38.338 --> 00:05:42.760
reason, exposes secrets to an unrelated destination, cannot be made

95
00:05:42.760 --> 00:05:47.116
sufficiently reversible, or carries harm too large for an ordinary

96
00:05:47.116 --> 00:05:47.624
confirmation.

97
00:05:47.624 --> 00:05:51.166
In our story, searching and drafting are automatic.

98
00:05:51.166 --> 00:05:56.100
Booking the selected table and sharing the minimum contact detail require

99
00:05:56.100 --> 00:05:56.393
confirmation.

100
00:05:56.393 --> 00:06:01.631
Sending a home address or hidden profile to an unrelated public endpoint is

101
00:06:01.631 --> 00:06:01.636
The categories are clear;

102
00:06:01.636 --> 00:06:02.195
blocked.

103
00:06:03.309 --> 00:06:06.376
now they must be enforced by the system.

104
00:06:06.376 --> 00:06:10.021
Build the matrix by capability, not by prompt wording.

105
00:06:10.021 --> 00:06:15.120
List every action the agent can take, the data it can touch, the destination

106
00:06:15.120 --> 00:06:19.950
it can reach, the external effect it creates, and the response tier that

107
00:06:19.950 --> 00:06:20.360
controls it.

108
00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:22.290
Separate reading from sending.

109
00:06:22.290 --> 00:06:27.030
A tool that can inspect a calendar should not automatically be able to

110
00:06:27.030 --> 00:06:27.415
invite guests.

111
00:06:27.415 --> 00:06:31.447
A tool that can draft an email should not automatically transmit it.

112
00:06:31.447 --> 00:06:36.236
A browser that can read a page should not automatically upload private

113
00:06:36.236 --> 00:06:36.320
files.

114
00:06:36.320 --> 00:06:39.175
Protect data before the model makes a decision.

115
00:06:39.175 --> 00:06:44.488
Hide secrets the task does not need, expose only minimum fields, allowlist

116
00:06:44.488 --> 00:06:49.657
known destinations, and run untrusted applications in a sandbox that can

117
00:06:49.657 --> 00:06:51.576
detect unexpected communication.

118
00:06:51.576 --> 00:06:54.827
Limit consequences with deterministic controls.

119
00:06:54.827 --> 00:07:00.512
Use spending caps, refund limits, narrow OAuth scopes, one-time credentials,

120
00:07:00.512 --> 00:07:06.198
dry runs, reversible staging, rate limits, and a second approval for actions

121
00:07:06.198 --> 00:07:08.922
whose impact crosses a defined threshold.

122
00:07:08.922 --> 00:07:11.837
Design confirmation as a decision surface.

123
00:07:11.837 --> 00:07:17.700
Show the exact restaurant, time, deposit, cancellation rule, contact

124
00:07:17.700 --> 00:07:19.205
details, and destination.

125
00:07:19.205 --> 00:07:21.761
Put risky changes in plain language.

126
00:07:21.761 --> 00:07:26.425
Let the user edit the payload, choose a safer scope, or cancel without

127
00:07:26.425 --> 00:07:27.958
losing the rest of the work.

128
00:07:27.958 --> 00:07:31.068
Define block conditions before the agent runs.

129
00:07:31.068 --> 00:07:35.741
Secret exfiltration, a new public endpoint with no task need, destructive

130
00:07:35.741 --> 00:07:40.221
action without recovery, and high-impact behavior that contradicts the

131
00:07:40.221 --> 00:07:44.253
user's instruction should stop immediately with a clear explanation.

132
00:07:44.253 --> 00:07:47.180
Log the path, not only the final result.

133
00:07:47.180 --> 00:07:51.727
Record which external content influenced the decision, which tool was

134
00:07:51.727 --> 00:07:56.604
requested, what data was selected, which control allowed or denied it, and

135
00:07:56.604 --> 00:07:57.575
what the user confirmed.

136
00:07:57.575 --> 00:08:01.430
This makes incidents explainable and policies improvable.

137
00:08:01.430 --> 00:08:06.745
Test the controls with three kinds of material: normal content, ambiguous

138
00:08:06.745 --> 00:08:09.368
content, and deliberately malicious content.

139
00:08:09.368 --> 00:08:13.075
Check both the final environment state and the process trace.

140
00:08:13.075 --> 00:08:17.556
A safe-looking answer is not enough if the agent attempted a forbidden

141
00:08:17.556 --> 00:08:18.062
transmission.

142
00:08:18.062 --> 00:08:20.912
Use the human-agent analogy from OpenAI.

143
00:08:20.912 --> 00:08:25.114
Ask what a careful customer-service employee could do alone, what a

144
00:08:25.114 --> 00:08:28.434
supervisor would review, and what no employee should do at all.

145
00:08:28.434 --> 00:08:34.528
Then translate those boundaries into tools, scopes, limits, and confirmation

146
00:08:34.528 --> 00:08:34.663
rules.

147
00:08:34.663 --> 00:08:39.816
Your reusable matrix has five columns: action or tool, data touched,

148
00:08:39.816 --> 00:08:44.209
destination, external effect and reversibility, and response tier.

149
00:08:44.209 --> 00:08:49.147
Fill it before connecting a new tool, then update it whenever the tool gains

150
00:08:49.147 --> 00:08:49.880
a new capability.

151
00:08:49.880 --> 00:08:52.090
Now solve the birthday dinner again.

152
00:08:52.090 --> 00:08:55.133
The agent automatically researches and drafts.

153
00:08:55.133 --> 00:08:59.995
It asks before booking and before sending the minimum contact detail to the

154
00:08:59.995 --> 00:09:00.601
chosen restaurant.

155
00:09:00.601 --> 00:09:06.260
It blocks the fake verification endpoint, explains why, and continues with a

156
00:09:06.260 --> 00:09:07.002
safer route.

157
00:09:07.002 --> 00:09:09.587
The malicious sentence was only the source.

158
00:09:09.587 --> 00:09:13.759
Risk appeared when it could reach private data and a consequential sink.

159
00:09:13.759 --> 00:09:18.702
The safest system assumes some manipulation will get through and limits what

160
00:09:18.702 --> 00:09:19.415
can happen next.

161
00:09:19.415 --> 00:09:24.688
Use Automatic for low-consequence, reversible work inside the user's intent

162
00:09:24.688 --> 00:09:26.924
with no sensitive external transmission.

163
00:09:26.924 --> 00:09:30.896
Keep the scopes narrow even when no confirmation is needed.

164
00:09:30.896 --> 00:09:36.373
Use Confirm for legitimate external changes, payments, commitments, new

165
00:09:36.373 --> 00:09:38.520
recipients, or sensitive transfers.

166
00:09:38.520 --> 00:09:44.379
Show the exact payload, destination, purpose, consequence, and safer

167
00:09:44.379 --> 00:09:45.089
alternative.

168
00:09:45.089 --> 00:09:49.954
Use Block for actions that conflict with the goal, lack a legitimate need,

169
00:09:49.954 --> 00:09:54.623
expose secrets to an unrelated destination, or create irreversible harm

170
00:09:54.623 --> 00:09:55.981
beyond the permitted boundary.

171
00:09:55.981 --> 00:09:59.388
Build these rules into the tools, not into hope.

172
00:09:59.388 --> 00:10:01.023
Follow Tiny Agent.

173
00:10:01.023 --> 00:10:04.167
Tiny Agent helps you get better at using AI.
